ce:section.ce:para:
TEM observation on the as-prepared C-dots (Fig. 1
                     a) reveals that they are monodisperse with sizes of 2–3 nm. High-resolution TEM (HRTEM) image (inset of Fig. 1a) confirmed the crystalline feature of the investigated C-dots with clear-cut lattice fringes. Raman spectra (Fig. 1b), measured with 633 nm laser excitation, were adopted to analyze the structure of C-dots. Similar to the previously reported cases [21,24], both G band (1545 cm−1) assigned to graphitic sp2 carbon and D band (1340 cm−1) originated from the disorder structures or defects on the surface of C-dots were observed. Additionally, XPS measurement was utilized to determine the actual chemical compositions of C-dots, where C1s (∼284 eV), N1s (∼400 eV) and O1s (∼531 eV) signals are clearly detected (Fig. 1c). The C, N, O contents in C-dots are about 51.5, 22.5 and 26.0 mol% (Table 1
                     ), respectively, confirming these C-dots are N-doped carbon-rich nanodots. As revealed in the high-resolution N1s XPS spectrum (Fig. 1d), two Gaussian bands corresponding to pyrrolic N (399.5 eV) and quaternary N (401.2 eV) [25] can be resolved. The dominant pyrrolic N in N1s XPS spectrum indicates that N is located on the surface of C-dot.
